            <div><b>Case Study2: Arts-based approaches to assess Cultural Ecosystem Services in the East Marine Plan area.</b></div>
            As part of the Cefas Seascapes project, we explored the use of arts-based approaches to capture Cultural Ecosystem Services from marine and coastal environments. We held four workshops in Lowestoft and Great Yarmouth, engaging participants in creating photomontages that reflected their personal connections to the marine and coastal environment. The process resulted in the production of a diverse range of artwork and interviews that captured participants thoughts and a narrative about what they had portrayed in their art works. It provided a richer understanding of the values of Cultural Ecosystem Services than traditional survey methods alone. This kind of evidence can complement traditional economic methods to inform more holistic trade-off analysis and decision making that takes into account what people value.     
        </p>                                        
